##############################################################################
                             REQUIRED REFERENCES
##############################################################################

 The theoretical foundation and first benchmark data of the relativistic
 four-component real-time time-dependent electron dynamics DFT approach
 were presented in Ref [1]. In addition, the work introduced an analytic
 form of the delta-type impulse, as well as a transition density matrix
 analysis (TDMA) that facilitates the interpretation of spectral transitions
 in terms of ground-state molecular orbitals. Application of the electron
 dynamics to the near L-edge X-ray absorption spectroscopy was discussed
 in Ref [2], along side with a selective perturbation (SP) that enables to
 represent the perturbation and response operators only in a selected set
 of molecular orbitals and by this means to address a specific spectral
 region and eliminate nonphysical excitations in RT-TDDFT simulations.
 A two-component variant of RT-TDDFT facilitating X2C Hamiltonian was
 formulated in Ref [3]. The theoretical foundation and first benchmark
 data of two- and four-component RT-TDDFT for the calculation of electron
 circular dichroism and optical rotatory dispersion spectra were given in
 Ref [4]. In addition, the resolution-of-the-identity approximation for
 the Coulomb term (RI-J) was introduced into RT-TDDFT.

 [1] M. Repisky, L. Konecny, M. Kadek, S. Komorovsky, O. L. Malkin,
     V. G. Malkin, and K. Ruud, J. Chem. Theory Comput. 11, 980-991 (2015)
     [DOI: https://doi.org/10.1021/ct501078d]

 [2] M. Kadek, L. Konecny, B. Gao, M. Repisky, and K. Ruud
     Phys. Chem. Chem. Phys. 17, 22566-22570 (2015)
     [DOI: https://doi.org/10.1039/C5CP03712C]

 [3] L. Konecny, M. Kadek, S. Komorovsky, O. L. Malkina, K. Ruud,
     and M. Repisky, J. Chem. Theory Comput. 12, 5823-5833 (2016)
     [DOI: https://doi.org/10.1021/acs.jctc.6b00740]

 [4] L. Konecny, M. Kadek, S. Komorovsky, K. Ruud, and M. Repisky
     J. Chem. Phys. 149, 204104 (2018)
     [DOI: https://doi.org/10.1063/1.5051032]

 XCFun: a library of DFT exchange-correlation functionals

 [5] U. Ekström, et al., J. Chem. Theory Comput. 6, 1971-1980 (2010)
     [DOI: https://doi.org/10.1021/ct100117s]


